# Roadmap — Finance PWA

## Design track — visual direction and acceptance

The product UI follows the supplied reference: dark-first Liquid Glass finance dashboard with navy depth, blue/cyan primary accents, translucent grouped surfaces, restrained glow, strong amount hierarchy and a persistent central “+” action. This track may change presentation and the application navigation/UI layer where required for a working screen. Domain rules, data contracts, storage, sync, OAuth and API architecture remain stable unless a documented missing capability requires a minimal additive change.

### Completed visual scope — Stages 1–3

- Reworked the application shell, dashboard surfaces, quick actions, transaction rows, account cards, planning cards, modal forms, FAB and bottom navigation.
- Added responsive desktop two-column composition and mobile single-column composition with iPhone safe-area support.
- Added consistent glass tokens: border, blur, radius, elevation, focus state, primary blue, income green and expense/error red.
- Kept existing handlers, selectors, forms, persistence and Google Sync flows intact while introducing a screen state and shared SVG icon system.
- Added real screens for overview, quick add, operations, accounts, budgets, goals, statistics, categories, settings and synchronization.
- Added a real custom-category form and real statistics derived from local transactions; these are the only new application-level behaviors in this pass.
- Added reduced-motion handling and visible keyboard focus states.

### Visual scope for future stages

- Stage 4: charts, exchange-rate cards, period filters and exports use the same dashboard grid and data-state treatment.
- Stage 5: onboarding, settings, offline/sync states, PWA standalone mode and safe-area behavior receive the same component-level polish and accessibility checks.
- Stage 6: release gate includes desktop and iPhone screenshots/smoke checks, no overflow, no unreadable contrast and no visually empty implemented screen.

### Design definition of done

Every visible feature must have loading, success, validation/error, empty and offline/pending states where applicable; use real data and existing application logic. A visual task is complete only when `npm run test`, `npm run build` and the relevant Playwright smoke flow pass.

### Current implementation note

The reference-aligned shell and all 10 screen entry points are implemented. Pixel-level parity still requires iterative browser screenshot comparison at the target desktop and iPhone dimensions. Google OAuth remains environment-dependent: the configured client must accept the exact current origin and `/oauth/callback` redirect URI.

## Stage 3 verification update — completed 2026-07-18

Local test configuration is now present in `.env.local` for the supplied web OAuth client ID. The intended authorized JavaScript origin is `http://localhost:5173`.

Manual browser verification on `http://localhost:5173` passed for app loading, Google Sync action initiation, loading/disabled state, and recovery from an unavailable OAuth window. The OAuth failure now resolves after 10 seconds with a user-facing retry message instead of leaving the action stuck.

The local OAuth flow was changed to a redirect-based implicit token flow for popup-restricted browsers. Manual verification reached the Google account chooser with the supplied client ID. Google then returned the precise `redirect_uri_mismatch` error: the requested URI is `http://localhost:5173/oauth/callback`, but that exact URI is not registered under the same OAuth Web Client ID. No access token was received and no spreadsheet write was attempted.

